Code Segment:Instruction Pointer, CS:IP
    the point of memory where code is executed

Data Segment:Source Index, DS:SI
    the point in memory where its reading data

Heap: last in first out memory, 
    Stack segment:stack pointer SS:SP
    push puts onto stack, pop retrieves from stack
    Stack pointer starts at top of stack, push lowers it and pop raises it

GDT: global descriptor table
    records and describes segments of memory, used to go from 16bit to 32bit
    In older systems, segments were used, which means you would set a base (start address) and limit (size) for each segment in GDT
        now, we use paging, so we can set all gdt elements to take the max supported size and base 0, and paging figures it out

PIC: Converts interupts to vectors that go to CPU, transfers hardware int to software
    master and slave pic, this allows more hardware interupts
    master takes commands and data on port 0x20 and 0x21
    slave takes commands and data on port 0xA0 and 0xA1
        slave puts all interupts into a port on master
    IRQ0-7 goes to master, 8-15 to slave
    We need to remap it because it overlaps with with CPU exceptions

IDT: Interupt descriptor table
    describes what to do when cpu is interrupted, such as by keyboard input

PMM: Physical memory manager
VMM: Virtual memory manager

Paging: a translation layer to access memory. 
    Allows better organization of memory, compartmentalisation, permissions etc
    64 bit allows 5 levels, PML5 (Page Map Level 5), PML4, PDPT (Page descriptor page table), PD and PT
        we're only using up to PML4
        by not defining PT, we use PD as the "page size", or size of roughly 2mb instead of 4kb
    Recursive paging: We use the first 9 bits of the address (48 bits) to point to PML4
        this essentially moves everything up one, so PD acts as PT, the entries in PD are now treated as pages, instead of links to another table
        this then maps the PT tables, so we have access to the physical memory that they are at
        it can be repeated, so mapping 18 bits treats PD tables as entries, so we can access PT tables and this repeats to access all levels

Functions:
    Print: prints string stored in si until 0
    printChar: prints char stored in al
    newLine: moves cursor to start of line and moves down one line
    getKey: processes input, adds to buffer and writes to screen. Key is written to al, enter is 0x0A
    compareString: compares string in si and di, returns al=1 if equal